      <div class="content-section"><div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Overview</span><h2>What Are Mid Cap Funds?</h2></div>
        <p>Mid cap mutual funds invest a minimum of 65% of their assets in stocks of companies ranked 101st to 250th by market capitalization as per SEBI norms. These companies typically have market caps between ₹15,000 crore and ₹75,000 crore and represent businesses in their growth phase — established enough to have proven business models yet small enough to offer significant upside potential.</p>
        <p>Mid cap companies are often tomorrow's large caps. Many of today's blue-chip stocks — like Bajaj Finance, Avenue Supermarts (DMart), and PI Industries — were mid caps just 5–10 years ago. By investing in mid cap funds, you're positioning your portfolio to capture this transition from growing companies to market leaders.</p>
        <p>Over the past decade, the Nifty Midcap 150 index has outperformed the Nifty 50 by 3%–5% annually, delivering approximately 16%–18% CAGR. However, this higher return comes with higher volatility — mid caps can fall 35%–45% during market corrections. This makes mid cap funds suitable for investors with at least a 5–7 year horizon and the ability to stomach short-term fluctuations.</p>
      </div>

