      <div class="content-section"><div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Benefits</span><h2>Why Invest in Mid Cap Funds?</h2></div>
        <ul class="feature-list">
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Superior Growth Potential</strong><p>Mid cap companies are in their high-growth phase with expanding market share, increasing revenues, and improving profitability. Many are on the path to becoming large caps, offering multi-bagger potential over 5–10 years.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Best Risk-Reward Balance</strong><p>Mid caps offer the sweet spot — better returns than large caps (3%–5% higher annually) without the extreme volatility of small caps. They combine established business fundamentals with meaningful growth runway.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Under-Researched Alpha Opportunity</strong><p>Mid cap stocks are less tracked by analysts compared to large caps, creating pricing inefficiencies. Skilled fund managers can identify undervalued mid cap gems before the market catches on, generating significant alpha.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Sector Diversification</strong><p>Mid cap funds provide exposure to niche sectors and emerging industries (specialty chemicals, healthcare, fintech) that are underrepresented in the large cap universe, adding diversification to your portfolio.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>SIP Advantage in Volatile Markets</strong><p>Mid cap volatility actually benefits SIP investors through rupee cost averaging. When prices dip, your SIP buys more units at lower prices, significantly reducing average cost and boosting long-term returns.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Proven Historical Outperformance</strong><p>Over 10+ year periods, mid cap funds have consistently outperformed large cap funds and broad market indices. ₹10,000 monthly SIP in mid caps for 10 years at 17% CAGR would grow to approximately ₹30 lakh.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section"><div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">How to Invest</span><h2>How to Invest in Mid Cap Funds</h2></div>
        <div class="steps-grid">
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">1</div><h3>Assess Your Risk Profile</h3><p>Mid caps are suitable for investors with moderate-to-high risk tolerance and a minimum 5–7 year horizon. Ensure you won't need this money for short-term goals.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">2</div><h3>Select Top-Performing Funds</h3><p>Choose funds with consistent 3–5 year track records, experienced fund managers, and reasonable expense ratios. Look for funds that outperform the Nifty Midcap 150 benchmark across market cycles.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">3</div><h3>Start SIP for Best Results</h3><p>SIP is highly recommended for mid cap funds due to their volatility. Start with ₹2,000–₹5,000/month and increase annually. SIP smooths out market ups and downs over time.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">4</div><h3>Hold Through Market Cycles</h3><p>Mid caps can underperform for 1–2 years during bear markets. Stay invested and continue SIPs — the subsequent bull phase typically delivers outsized returns that more than compensate for the drawdowns.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
