  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Mid Cap Funds</h2></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the ideal allocation to mid cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>For a moderate risk investor, 20%–30% of the equity portfolio in mid cap funds is recommended. For aggressive investors, this can go up to 40%. Always ensure you have a strong large cap core (50%+) before adding mid cap satellite holdings. Young investors with longer time horizons can afford higher mid cap allocations.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Should I invest lump sum or SIP in mid cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>SIP is strongly recommended for mid cap funds due to their higher volatility. SIP automatically buys more units during dips, reducing average cost. If you have a lump sum, consider deploying via STP (Systematic Transfer Plan) over 6–12 months from a liquid fund rather than investing all at once.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How do mid cap funds perform during market crashes?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Mid caps typically fall more than large caps during crashes — 35%–45% vs 25%–30%. However, they also recover faster and rally more during bull markets. During 2020, mid cap funds fell ~40% but rallied over 100% in the following 12 months. This asymmetry rewards patient investors who stay through downturns.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What is the difference between mid cap and flexi cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Mid cap funds must invest at least 65% in mid cap stocks (ranked 101-250). Flexi cap funds can invest across all market capitalizations without minimum allocation requirements. Flexi cap offers the fund manager flexibility to shift between large, mid, and small caps based on market conditions, while mid cap provides focused exposure to the mid cap segment.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>When is the best time to invest in mid cap funds?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>With SIP, anytime is the right time — dollar cost averaging removes timing concerns. For lump sum, market corrections offer better entry points as mid cap valuations become more attractive. Avoid investing large sums when mid cap P/E ratios are at all-time highs. But rather than trying to time the market, consistent SIP investing delivers the best long-term results.</p></div></div></div>
    </div>
  </div></section>

